Comment: A quick little blitz game i had on my lunch break awhile ago.
At this point i was thinking KID.
Developing my Knight and adding a defender to d4.
He prepares to fianchetto his dark squared bishop.

Using the wings to help control the center of the board. I also like putting my queen on the c2 square along with the light squared bishop on d3. I like having control of that b1-h7 diagonal as well as having my pieces aimed at the King side.
He fianchetto's his dark squared Bishop.
Develops another minor piece as well as prepares for e4.

Preparing for an e5 pawn push. At this current juncture i really wasn't sure where i wanted the direction of this game to go. I tend to like having the b1-h7 diagonal open for my queen and bishop, which helps when going for a King side attack.
Taking firm control of the center of the board. Common in the KID.
Further preparation e5. If the pawn is pushed prematurely, then dxe5. If dxe5, an exchange of queens would leave black without the ability to castle.
Bolstering up the center pawn as well as getting my bishop on that diagonal.
the e5 pawn push. I really didn't want a closed game, so i was very hesitant about d5.
Keeping the tension in the center as well as aiming my pieces at the King side.
I'm not sure about this move? It breaks the tension but other than that i can't really find a purpose for taking.

Taking back with the knight. Here i like my position. I wouldn't say white has a huge advantage, however white does have a lead in development as well as more space and control in the center. Black's light squared bishop is also temporarily blocked in.
I really don't want to exchange right now. I would much rather keep the complexity of the board.
Reinforcing c4. From here i wanted to get my king to a safe place and remove his knight from the center of the board. Other than that i really don't have a solid plan of action.
